tr: thrown together in a disorderly fashion

example.ex: Tourists were scrambling over the rocks looking for the perfect camera angle...
example.tran: 游客们在正爬上岩石寻找最佳的拍摄角度。

example.ex: He scrambled up a steep bank.
example.tran: 他攀上了一个陡峭的河堤。

value.def: If you scramble over rocks or up a hill, you move quickly over them or up it using your hands to help you.

example.ex: Ann threw back the covers and scrambled out of bed...
example.tran: 安掀开被子，急忙下了床。

value.def: If you scramble to a different place or position, you move there in a hurried, awkward way.

example.ex: More than three million fans are expected to scramble for tickets...
example.tran: 预计会有超过 300 万的球迷抢购门票。

example.ex: Business is booming and foreigners are scrambling to invest.
example.tran: 商业繁荣，外国人争相投资。

example.ex: ...a scramble to get a seat on the early morning flight.

gramarinfo.label: usu sing, oft N <l>for</l> n, N to-inf

value.def: If a number of people scramble for something, they compete energetically with each other for it.

example.ex: Make the toast and scramble the eggs.
example.tran: 把面包烤一下并炒些鸡蛋。

value.def: If you scramble eggs, you break them, mix them together and then heat and stir the mixture in a pan.

example.ex: The latest machines scramble the messages so that the conversation cannot easily be intercepted.
example.tran: 最新的机器对信号作扰频处理，通话就不易被侦听了。

value.def: If a device scrambles a radio or telephone message, it interferes with the sound so that the message can only be understood by someone with special equipment.
value.tran: 倒换(无线电或电话信号)的频率(使只有持特殊仪器的人才能接收)
